[1] Note that, in the situation where you have extreme outliers, this can be due to:
[1] 1) data entry errors, measurement errors or unusual values.
[1] You can include the outlier in the analysis anyway if you do not believe the result will be substantially affected.
[1] This can be evaluated by comparing the result of the ANOVA test with and without the outlier.
[1] It’s also possible to keep the outliers in the data and perform robust ANOVA test using the WRS2 package.
[1] 
[1] 
[1] 2) Checking normality assumption
[1] # Building the linear model
[1] # Creating a QQ plot of residuals
[1] ### Compute Shapiro-Wilk test of normality ###
# A tibble: 1 × 3
  variable         statistic  p.value
  <chr>                <dbl>    <dbl>
1 residuals(model)     0.696 1.98e-18
[1] The normality assumption is not supported by the Shapiro-Wilk test. The p-value is significant (p = 1.97868642958569e-18),
[1] so we cannot assume normality for this dataset.
[1] 
[1] 3) Checking homogeneity of variance assumption
[1] This can be checked using the Levene’s test:
# A tibble: 1 × 4
    df1   df2 statistic       p
  <int> <int>     <dbl>   <dbl>
1     2   189      5.48 0.00486
[1] The Levene’s test is not significant (p > 0.00485674456083548). Therefore, we can assume the homogeneity of variances in the different groups.
[1] ### Computation of the one-way ANOVA test ###
[1] In the R code below, the asterisk represents the interaction effect and the main effect of each variable (and all lower-order interactions).
# A tibble: 1 × 6
  .y.        n statistic    df     p method        
* <chr>  <int>     <dbl> <int> <dbl> <chr>         
1 values   192      4.51     2 0.105 Kruskal-Wallis
[1] There was no statistically significant interaction between loci
[1] 
[1] ### Post-hoct tests ###
[1] ### Procedure for significant one-way interaction ###
[1] ### Compute pairwise comparisons ###
[1] To determine which group means are different. We’ll now perform multiple pairwise comparisons between the different conditions.
[1] You can run and interpret all possible pairwise comparisons using a Bonferroni adjustment.
[1] This can be easily done using the function emmeans_test() [rstatix package], a wrapper around the emmeans package,
[1] which needs to be installed. Emmeans stands for estimated marginal means (aka least square means or adjusted means).
